Exploration of the factors that influenced students' math scores in PISA data¶

by Erin Yuan¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The original dataset is extremely large and difficult to read. Therefore, I decided to take out some interesting columns and formed a new csv file called "new_data" so I don't need to wait for loading every time I run the codes.

data = data.drop(columns = {'PV1MATH','PV2MATH','PV3MATH','PV4MATH','PV5MATH'}, axis = 1)

# change some data types 
#gender
df.gender = df.gender.astype('category')
# set 'job_status' as ordered categories
job = ['Working full-time <for pay>','Working part-time <for pay>','Not working, but looking for a job','Other (e.g. home duties, retired) ']
job_class =  pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = job)
df['mother_job_status'] =df['mother_job_status'].astype(job_class) 
df['father_job_status'] = df['father_job_status'].astype(job_class) 
# set 'teacher interes' as ordered categories
teacher_int = ['Every Lesson','Most Lessons','Some Lessons','Never or Hardly Ever']
teacher_int_class = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = teacher_int)
df['teacher_show_interest'] = df['teacher_show_interest'].astype(teacher_int_class)
# set 'listen in class' as ordered categories
agree_list = ['Strongly agree','Agree','Disagree','Strongly disagree']
agree_class = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,categories = agree_list)
df['listen_in_class'] = df['listen_in_class'].astype(agree_class)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • All of the columns contain more than 250,000 non-null data.
  • Numerical columns are "International Grade", "wealth", "time of computer use", "mathematical interest", and "math scores".
  • Non-numerical columns are "country", "gender", "mother job status", "father job status", "listen in class", and "teacher show interest.
  • Non-numerical columns, except "country" and "gender" are ordered variables. The orders are:
    • (worst) > (best)
    • mother job status: Working full-time (for pay), Working part-time (for pay), Not working but looking for a job, Other (e.g. home duties, retired)
    • father job status: Working full-time (for pay), Working part-time (for pay), Not working but looking for a job, Other (e.g. home duties, retired)
    • listen in class: Strongly agree, Agree, Disagree, Strongly disagree
    • teacher show interest: Every Lesson, Most Lessons, Some Lessons, Never or Hardly Ever

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I would like to find out what factors influence students' math scores most.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I would expect that mother and father's job status would have some impacts on children's education. But I'm not sure if math scores would be impacted specifically. Wealth should make some differences as well. I would love to find out whether there are relationships between the other factors and students' math grades.

In [366]:
def violinplot(x, y, **kwargs):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.violinplot(x, y, color =base_color, inner = 'quartile' )
g = sb.PairGrid(data = df, x_vars = categorical, y_vars = numerical, size =3)
g.map(violinplot);

A few findings from these violinplots are:

  • There are almost no difference for any numerical data between females and males. Maybe we need to use other plot forms.
  • Parents' job status has no impact as well.
  • Students who believe that listening in class was not important generally had less mathmetical interest and performed slightly worse than students who listened in class.
  • Teachers who showed most interest resulted in slighly worse math scores of students, and teachers who hardly ever showed interest led to less interest in students towards math as well.

We are going to focus our exploration on "listen_in_class" and "teacher_show_interest" factors.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

From the bivariate analyses, some relationship can be drawn from the graphs. For example, male students expressed more mathematical interest than female students. And male students made a higher average math scores in general. Further analysis among math scores, wealth, and time of computer use need to be conducted in order to draw a conclusion. Interestingly, teachers who show interest in every lession did not lead to the highest math scores from students. But teachers who show interest in most lessons helped students achieve the highest math scores in general.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Teachers' interest in class had a direct relationship with students' mathematical interest. Teachers who showed interest in every lession resulted in highest students' interest towards math and teachers who hardly showed any interest resulted in lowest students' interest. Students who believe that listening in class is extremely helpful showed the highest mathematical interest and enjoyed least computer use.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

It's clear now that both listen_in_class and teacher_show_interest had influence on students' interest and math scores. However, based on the analysis in the univariate section, there is no direct relationship between mathematical interest and math scores.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It's interesting the find out that some factors in the dataframe were not correlated at all, such as 'father_job_status' and "mother_job_status". It's probably because the data collection is not complete since there were no data for the choice of full_time (for pay) within job_status column. Also, wealth and computer use had little effect on math scores as well.
